Negative Interest Rate Club
Brussels – Central banks have made only limited progress over much of the last decade in stemming the powerful global deflationary forces.
Since 2008, the US Federal Reserve has maintained interest rates at zero while also expanding its balance sheet on an unprecedented scale through multiple rounds of quantitative easing (QE).
The Bank of England, the Bank of Japan, and the European Central Bank followed suit, each implementing its own version of what is known as “quantitative easing” (QE).
Inflation has failed to gain a reasonable foothold anywhere.
Though these countries are all battling deflationary pressures, their monetary policies – as well as economic performance – are diverging.
The US and UK are now growing strongly enough to exit expansionary policies and raise interest rates, whereas the eurozone and Japan are ramping up QE, pushing policy long-term interest rates further into negative territory.
Why is there this difference?
Briefly, it is debt.
For decades, the US and the UK have run current-account deficits, making them debtor nations, while the eurozone and Japan have had external surpluses, making them creditor nations.
Negative interest rates benefit debtor countries but not creditor countries, so the negative interest rates introduced after the global economic crisis stimulated the recovery of the US and the UK, but were largely ineffective for the Eurozone and Japan.
This is not an isolated phenomenon.
To date, most creditor countries – nations with sustained large current account surpluses, such as Denmark and Switzerland – have negative interest rates, not just for long-term government bonds and other "risk-free" debts, but also for medium-term bonds.
This is not good.
Despite the limited effectiveness of low interest rates, these economies' central banks still adhere to this policy.
If they argue that QE or lowering interest rates cannot benefit the economy, they will sidestep the issue and counter the notion that raising rates can stimulate the economy — seemingly without flaw.
In reality, this is full of holes.
Basic economics courses mention the peculiar phenomenon of the "backward-bending supply of savings curve": under certain conditions, lowering interest rates leads to increased savings.
Because lower interest rates reduce savers' income, they will cut back on spending, especially if their goal is to save for retirement.
All of these points do not negate the general rule — which forms the basis of modern monetary policy — that lowering interest rates can stimulate consumption and other types of spending.
Only the impact varies due to differences in the debt condition of economies.
In a closed economy, each creditor has a debtor, so regardless of what creditors may lose due to extremely low interest rates, debtors should benefit.
But in an economy with substantial net foreign asset positions, there will naturally be more creditors than debtors.
For a country with substantial foreign debts, the situation is reversed.
Therefore, the effect of lower bound monetary policy differs between creditor and debtor economies.
Until recently, this condition was not important because foreign asset positions were typically small (in percent of GDP).
But today, the foreign asset positions of the major industrialized economies are large and increasingly diversified, partly because of the leveraging that contributed to the global financial crisis of 2007-2008.
In fact, leverage continues to rise at the national level.
While overall current account imbalances have moderated since the financial crisis, they have not reversed.
This means that surplus countries are continuing to strengthen their creditor position, creating a divergence with deficit economies.
Some major commodity exporters, such as Russia and Saudi Arabia, had large current account surpluses when oil prices were high, becoming the main exceptions to the global trend of rising foreign asset positions.
Since June 2014, world oil prices have fallen dramatically, reversing these countries' wealth trends.
Their export earnings have drastically declined – many countries have seen cuts of more than half – forcing them into deficits, relying on large sovereign wealth funds accumulated during the commodities boom.
Significant spending cuts are now inevitable.
Industrialized economies face a completely different set of challenges.
They have a luxury problem – to some extent – ensuring that consumers spend the unexpected windfall from import price declines.
But in creditor countries, negative interest rates do not seem to be advancing this goal; in fact, some external surpluses are even increasing.
This divergence exists within the eurozone as well.
Even though the eurozone as a whole is a creditor economy, it includes debtor countries.
Debtor economies, like Spain and Portugal, now often have current account surpluses and are reducing their debt.
But traditional debtor countries have such large current account surpluses that the asymmetry between debtor and creditor countries continues to increase.
The most concerning aspect is that Germany's current account surplus has increased to nearly 8% of GDP since the financial crisis, meaning that the surpluses Germany accumulated during this period surpassed the historical total.
Following current trends, Germany's creditor position could increase from 60% of GDP to 100%.
Central bank governors should be patient.
In fact, economists support the global trend toward central bank independence precisely because central bank governors are less inclined to stimulate short-term economic growth.
But central bank governors seem not to have much patience for low inflation, despite the gradual filling of the output gap, and despite full employment in the US and Japan.
Central bank governors of debt countries must stop manipulating their economies with more monetary easing that may be adverse to production.
Instead, they should allow recoveries to develop on their own, even if very slowly, and wait for the base effect from falling oil prices to fade away.
ECB governor Draghi recently admitted that current monetary policy approaches may not be effective in today’s global environment.
But promising more of the same is not the solution.
